              DEGAS GETTING HIS DAY IN PHILLY               

The latest exhibition of the works of Edgar Degas will soon 
open its doors in Philadelphia. The Inquirer notes that the 
name Degas will always be synonymous with "dance." This latest 
exhibition of the artist's work focuses in on myriad aspects 
of Terpsichore. More than half of the works of art that Degas 
completed before his death had something to do with dance or 
dancers. The publication's Edward J. Sozanski says that Degas 
managed to create some of "Western art's most transcendent 
images of dancers and dance performance." Due to open early 
next month, the Degas showing will be mounted at the 
Philadelphia Museum of Art. A co-organizer of the exhibit is 
the Detroit Institute of the Arts, which will display the works 
after they leave Philadelphia. The exhibit has more than 120 
pieces by Degas and is officially named "Degas and the Dance."

