More on the West Virginia "Bumpkins":

Brian, for what it's worth, the Pep Band at UVa has always been 
irreverent and makes fun of everyone, not just West Virginia. 
When I was in the band in 1975 we were banned from playing at 
Maryland games for a year because of a joke about their gover-
nor going to jail. I'll admit, it all seemed funnier when I 
was a student, but I don't think it was meant maliciously.
-Meg M.

Another example of too thin-skinned people who are too easily 
offended.  What about the sterotypes of Texans, Oklahomans, 
Arkansas residents, Mississippi, the Scandinavians in 
Minnesota/North Dakota/Wisconsin, Mormons in Utah, gangsters 
in New Jersey, and on and on and on.  Do we have so little to 
seriously be concerned about that we must take umbrage at every 
little slight?  Folks, get over it!!!!   People have been 
stereotyping Texans and Okies for years-----why is everyone 
trying to move down here, then????
-Proud native Texan.

Dear Brian, 
There is NO way, repeat, NO way to the Nth power, that schools 
can prevent insults like one school team calling another 
"Bumpkins" and worse. We, as a species, are just too hardwired 
to keep on 'dissing' each other. Is there ANY statement that 
cannot be considered an insult? School rivalry has been going 
on since the education institute started. Just tell everyone 
to grow a thick skin and stop taking yourself too seriously 
if you want to make your mark in the world of education, 
sports, business, or anywhere else. The question of insult 
would not even be an issue in most cases, except for the hor-
rendous lawsuits over it. If the USA adopted England's legal 
statue saying that the loser of such ridiculous class action 
suits must PAY for all the court and lawyer costs if he loses, 
these endless and unbelievably expensive to the taxpayer non-
sense suits would be almost non-existent. The only reason we 
don't do that in America is because it would mean less work 
for the lawyers! 
-Bob S.

